Most of answers (even recent) referencing JDK classes rely on [`File.delete()`][1] but that is a flawed API as the operation may fail silently.  
The `java.io.File.delete()` method documentation states :

&gt; Note that the `java.nio.file.Files` class defines the `delete` method to
&gt; throw an `IOException` when a file cannot be deleted. This is useful for
&gt; error reporting and to diagnose why a file cannot be deleted.


As replacement, you should favor [`Files.delete(Path p)`][2]  that throws an `IOException` with a error message.   

